# Raspberry Pi setup

This guide describes how to run `pi-camera` on Raspberry Pi OS.

## 1. Prepare the system

Update the system and install external tools used by the application:

```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y rpicam-apps ffmpeg network-manager
```

Verify that the camera tools are available:

```bash
rpicam-vid --version
rpicam-still --version
```

Test the camera outside the application:

```bash
rpicam-still -o test.jpg
```

## 2. Framebuffer display

The default framebuffer path is:

```text
/dev/fb0
```

Check whether it exists:

```bash
ls -l /dev/fb0
```

If your display uses another framebuffer device, pass it with:

```bash
--fb=/dev/fb1
```

## 3. Touchscreen

Find the touchscreen input device:

```bash
ls -l /dev/input/
cat /proc/bus/input/devices
```

Start the application with the selected event device:

```bash
--touch=/dev/input/event0
```

If the axes are inverted, use:

```bash
--invert-x=true
--invert-y=true
```

`invertY` defaults to `true` in the application.

## 4. GPIO buttons

Main shutter button:

```bash
--gpio-pin=17
```

Additional buttons:

```bash
--button-tab-pin=27
--button-mode-pin=22
--button-prev-pin=5
--button-next-pin=6
--button-gallery-pin=13
--button-video-pin=19
```

Buttons are configured as `InputPullUp`, so the simplest wiring is:

```text
GPIO ---- button ---- GND
```

## 5. Build and publish

From the project directory:

```bash
cd pi-camera-master/pi-camera
dotnet restore
dotnet publish -c Release -r linux-arm64 --self-contained true -o ./publish
```

For 32-bit Raspberry Pi OS, publish with `linux-arm` instead of `linux-arm64`:

```bash
dotnet publish -c Release -r linux-arm --self-contained true -o ./publish
```

Copy the published files to `/opt/pi-camera`:

```bash
sudo mkdir -p /opt/pi-camera
sudo cp -r ./publish/* /opt/pi-camera/
sudo chmod +x /opt/pi-camera/pi-camera
```

## 6. First manual start

```bash
sudo /opt/pi-camera/pi-camera \
  --fb=/dev/fb0 \
  --width=480 \
  --height=320 \
  --out=/home/admin/Pictures/PiCamera \
  --api=true \
  --api-url=http://0.0.0.0:5000
```

If everything works, the `CEGŁA` interface appears on the display and the web panel becomes available at:

```text
http://<RASPBERRY_PI_IP>:5000
```

Get the Raspberry Pi IP address with:

```bash
hostname -I
```

## 7. systemd service

Create a systemd unit:

```bash
sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/pi-camera.service
```

Paste:

```ini
[Unit]
Description=Pi Camera
After=network-online.target
Wants=network-online.target

[Service]
Type=simple
User=root
WorkingDirectory=/opt/pi-camera
ExecStart=/opt/pi-camera/pi-camera --fb=/dev/fb0 --width=480 --height=320 --out=/home/admin/Pictures/PiCamera --api=true --api-url=http://0.0.0.0:5000
Restart=on-failure
RestartSec=3

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
```

Enable and start the service:

```bash
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable pi-camera
sudo systemctl start pi-camera
```

View logs:

```bash
sudo journalctl -u pi-camera -f
```

## 8. Wi-Fi and hotspot

The application controls Wi-Fi through `nmcli`. Check NetworkManager status manually with:

```bash
nmcli radio wifi
nmcli connection show
```

Default hotspot settings:

```text
SSID: PiCamera
Password: picamera123
```

Override them with startup arguments:

```bash
--hotspot-ssid=MyCamera
--hotspot-pass=my-password-123
```

## 9. Battery status

The application tries to read battery status from:

1. a file passed through `--battery-file`,
2. `/sys/class/power_supply/*/capacity`,
3. a command passed through `--battery-command`.

Example using a file:

```bash
--battery-file=/tmp/battery_percent
```

Example using a command:

```bash
--battery-command="cat /sys/class/power_supply/BAT0/capacity"
```

The value can be either a number such as `74` or a percentage such as `74%`.

## 10. Troubleshooting

### Camera preview does not start

Test `rpicam-vid` directly:

```bash
rpicam-vid --codec mjpeg -t 3000 --width 480 --height 320 --nopreview -o test.mjpg
```

### Full HQ photo capture does not work

Test `rpicam-still` directly:

```bash
rpicam-still --nopreview --immediate -o test.jpg
```

### Video conversion fails

Check `ffmpeg`:

```bash
ffmpeg -version
```

If conversion fails, the temporary `*.rawmjpeg` source file is usually left in the output directory for debugging.

### Permission problems

For initial testing, run the application with `sudo`. For a production setup, configure the correct groups and `udev` rules for framebuffer, input and GPIO access.

### Web panel is not reachable

Check that the application was started with:

```bash
--api=true --api-url=http://0.0.0.0:5000
```

Then verify the Raspberry Pi IP and local firewall settings:

```bash
hostname -I
sudo ss -ltnp | grep 5000
```
